'''Decynium-22''' is a [[cation]]ic derivative of [[quinoline]], and a potent inhibitor of the [[plasma membrane monoamine transporter]] (PMAT),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tocris.com/dispprod.php?ItemId=364182#.VEAG3C6wKIg|title=Decynium 22|publisher=Tocris Bioscience|year=2014|accessdate=16 Oct 2014}}</ref> as well as all members of the [[organic cation transporter]] (OCT) family in both human and rat cells.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bts.ucsf.edu/fdatransportal/compounds/decynium-22/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20141017023701/http://bts.ucsf.edu/fdatransportal/compounds/decynium-22/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=17 October 2014 |title=Decynium-22 |publisher=University of California, San Francisco |accessdate=16 Oct 2014 }}</ref> However, it has little effect on high affinity [[monoamine]] transporters such as the [[dopamine transporter]] and [[norepinephrine transporter]].<ref name="pmid23875515">{{cite journal|vauthors=Inyushin M, Kucheryaykh Y, Kucheryavykh L, Sanabria P, Jiménez-Rivera C, Struganova I | title=Membrane potential and pH-dependent accumulation of decynium-22 (1,1′-diethyl-2,2′-cyanine iodide) fluorescence through the low affinity OCT transporters in astrocytes. | journal=Bol Asoc Med P R | year= 2010 | volume= 102 | issue= 3 | pages= 5–12 | pmid=23875515 | doi= | pmc=3721433 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>
==Transporter inhibition== Decynium has been shown to have a very high affinity to organic cation transporters in a variety of species, including human,<ref name="pmid8114944">{{cite journal|vauthors=Russ H, Sonna J, Keppler K, Baunach S, Schömig E | title=Cyanine-related compounds: a novel class of potent inhibitors of extraneuronal noradrenaline transport. | journal=Naunyn Schmiedebergs Arch Pharmacol | year= 1993 | volume= 348 | issue= 5 | pages= 458–65 | doi= 10.1007/bf00173203| pmc= | pmid=8114944 }}</ref><ref name="pmid12110607">{{cite journal|vauthors=Hayer-Zillgen M, Brüss M, Bönisch H | title=Expression and pharmacological profile of the human organic cation transporters hOCT1, hOCT2 and hOCT3. | journal=Br J Pharmacol | year= 2002 | volume= 136 | issue= 6 | pages= 829–36 | pmid=12110607 | doi=10.1038/sj.bjp.0704785 | pmc=1573414 }}</ref> rat,<ref name="pmid7990927">{{cite journal|vauthors=Gründemann D, Gorboulev V, Gambaryan S, Veyhl M, Koepsell H | title=Drug excretion mediated by a new prototype of polyspecific transporter. | journal=Nature | year= 1994 | volume= 372 | issue= 6506 | pages= 549–552 | doi=10.1038/372549a0 | pmc= | pmid=7990927 }}</ref> and pig.<ref name="pmid9099681">{{cite journal|vauthors=Gründemann D, Babin-Ebell J, Martel F, Ording N, Schmidt A, Schömig E | title=Primary structure and functional expression of the apical organic cation transporter from kidney epithelial LLC-PK1 cells. | journal=J Biol Chem | year= 1997 | volume= 272 | issue= 16 | pages= 10408–13 | doi= 10.1074/jbc.272.16.10408 | pmc= | pmid=9099681 }}</ref> Decynium-22 has been shown to block the uptake of [[1-methyl-4-phenylpyridinium]] (MPP) via the [[OCT3]] transporter in rat [[astrocytes]].<ref name="pmid12485400">{{cite journal|vauthors=Inazu M, Takeda H, Matsumiya T | title=Expression and functional characterization of the extraneuronal monoamine transporter in normal human astrocytes. | journal=J Neurochem | year= 2003 | volume= 84 | issue= 1 | pages= 43–52 | doi= 10.1046/j.1471-4159.2003.01566.x| pmc= | pmid=12485400 }}</ref>
==Fluorescence== Decynium-22 emits a low [[fluorescence]] yield (around 0.001), and in its monomeric form is a weakly fluorescent. However, aggregated decynium-22 emits a strong [[Superradiance|superradiant]] emission with a maximum near 570–580&nbsp;nm.<ref>Stiel H, Daehne S, Teuchner K. J-aggregates of pseudoisocyanine in solution: New data from nonlinear spectroscopy. J Lumines. 1988;39:351–357.</ref><ref>Struganova IA. Dynamics of formation of 1,1′-diethyl-2,2′-cyanine iodide J-aggregates in solution. J Physical Chem A. 2000;104:9670–9674.</ref> 480&nbsp;nm light falls near a short wavelength peak of the [[excitation spectrum]] of these aggregates. Decynium-22 fluorescence caused by aggregation can be observed in astrocytes.<ref name="pmid23875515" />
==Schizophrenia and depression== Decynium-22 has recently been investigated for its role in increasing [[extracellular]] [[serotonin]] in the brain in neuropharmacology research. The transportation of the neurotransmitter serotonin is often disrupted in psychiatric disorders characterized by social impairment, such as [[schizophrenia]] and [[Depression (mood)|depression]]. Serotonin is primarily taken up by the [[5-HT transporter]] (SERT), although it is also taken up by auxiliary transporters, known as "uptake 2", which include OCT and PMAT.
The most commonly prescribed antidepressant drugs are the [[selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors]] (SSRIs), which act by blocking the high affinity SERT. A proposed explanation for the limited efficacy of SSRIs is the presence of the low affinity transporters OCT and PMAT, which limit the ability of SSRIs to increase [[extracellular]] serotonin. Decynium-22 blocked serotonin uptake via these auxiliary transporters, and when used in conjunction with SSRIs, decynium-22 enhanced the effects of SSRIs to inhibit serotonin clearance.<ref name="pmid23785165">{{cite journal|vauthors=Horton RE, Apple DM, Owens WA, Baganz NL, Cano S, Mitchell NC | title=Decynium-22 enhances SSRI-induced antidepressant-like effects in mice: uncovering novel targets to treat depression. | journal=J Neurosci | year= 2013 | volume= 33 | issue= 25 | pages= 10534–43 | pmid=23785165 | doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.5687-11.2013 | pmc=3685842 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> A similar effect was seen in SERT [[knock-out mice]], which resulted in an improvement of social behavior.<ref name="pmid6860">{{cite journal|vauthors=Loginova LG, Iakovleva MB, Golovina IG, Bogdanova TI | title=[Yeast cell wall-dissolving enzymes of the thermotolerant actinomycete Thermoactinomyces vulgaris]. | journal=Mikrobiologiia | year= 1976 | volume= 45 | issue= 2 | pages= 291–7 | doi= | pmc= | pmid=6860 }}</ref> When OCT3 was knocked out in mice, however, decynium-22 was ineffectual, indicating that the anti-depressant effects of decynium-22 are dependent upon its blockage of the OCT3.<ref name="pmid23785165" />
